# Plain HTTP on port 80. This is the right choice for bring-your-own phones on
# a `.local` name: no certificate warnings (there is no warning-free HTTPS on a
# .local name), and the app advertises http://<this Pi's name>.local.
#
# Security here is the trusted LAN, not the transport — keep the device on an
# isolated network and never expose it to the internet.
#
# The site is matched by *shape*, not by a fixed name: any single-label .local
# host, so hallclock.local and hallclock-b.local (two halls on one LAN) are both
# served by the same shipped file. That matters because hall-clock-update.sh
# reinstalls this Caddyfile on every update — a hostname baked in here would be
# reverted on the next update, and a renamed Pi would start 404ing.
#
# Keeping the host matcher (rather than a bare :80) is deliberate: it means a
# request arriving with some other Host is not served at all, which is what turns
# away a DNS-rebinding attempt from an attacker-controlled domain. A .local name
# is mDNS-only and cannot be pointed at this Pi from outside the LAN.
#
# Phones use <name>.local; the on-Pi kiosk uses localhost so the TV display never
# depends on the Pi resolving its own .local name via mDNS.
http://*.local, http://localhost {
	# The app listens on a Unix socket (no TCP port). Caddy connects to it as a
	# member of the socket's group — see README "Zero-port Unix socket".
	reverse_proxy unix//run/hall-clock/app.sock
}
